                 *** Linux Basic Commands ***
    
    1. sudo su -  : (Super User DO) (Switch User) 
    ---> this command is used to login into root user account
    syntax: sudo su -

    2. pwd : (Present Working Directory)
    --> display current working directory
    syntax: pwd

    3. ls : (list)
    --> used to display contents of ditrectory/folder
    syntax: ls

    4. mkdir : (make directory)
    --> is used to create folder/dircetory.
    i] syntax: mkdir <folder_name>
       eg: mkdir  demo
   
   ii]syntax: mkdir <folder_name1> <folder_name2> <folder_name3> 
      eg: mkdir folder1 folder2 folder3

   iii]syntax: mkdir -p <parent_folder/child_folder>
   ---> used to create nested directories. here -p means parent
      eg: mkdir -p prod/dev

   5. rmdir : (remove directory)
    ---> to remove empty directories.
    syntax:  rmdir <folder_name>
      eg: rmdir  demo

   6. rm -rf : 
    --> to delete non empty directory.
   here,
   rm = remove
   -r = recursive
   -f = forcefully
   
   -r tells rm to recursively delete the directory and all its contents.

   "recursively" means that the command will operate on a directory and all subdirectories and files.

    **commands to create files in linux**

    7. touch :
   --> is used to create empty files.
   syntax: touch <file_name>
   eg: touch demo.txt

   8. cat > :
   --> this command is used to create file and write contents to it.
   i] syntax:  cat > <file_name>
   eg:  cat > demo.txt
   --> to save and exit use ctrl + d 

   ii] syntax: cat >> <file_name>
       eg:  cat >> demo.txt
       ---> used to append data (add data) into file.

   9. cat :
   --> this commmand is used to display file contents.
   syntax: cat <file_name>
   eg:  cat demo.txt

   10. cd : (Change Directory)
   --> this command is used to move in between directory.
   syntax: cd <directory_name>
   eg: cd folder1

   11. cd .. :
   --> this command is used to take you in previous directory
   syntax: cd ..

   12. rm : (remove)
   --> used to delete/remove files.
   syntax: rm <file_name>
   eg:  rm demo.txt

   13. cp : (copy)
   --> used to copy files 
   i] copy to folder
   syntax:  cp <file_name> < folder_name>
   eg:  cp demo.txt  folder1

   ii] copy to file
   syntax: cp <source_file_name> <dest_file_name>
   eg: cp demo.txt  file.txt

   14. cp -r :
   --> to copy folder
   syntax: cp -r <source_folder_name> <dest_folder_name>
   eg: cp -r folder test_folder

   15. mv : (move)
   --> mv has two use cases
   i] move file/folder:
   --> it is used to move files and directories from one location to another
   syntax: mv <source> <dest_folder_name>
   eg: mv file.txt folder

   ii] to rename file
   syntax: mv <old_file_name> <new_file_name>
   eg: mv demo  demo.txt

   16. head :
   --> this command is used to display the first few lines (10 lines) of the file.
   syntax: head <file_name>
   eg: head myfile.txt
   syntax: head -n <file_name>
   eg: head -5 myfile.txt
   --> to display 5 lines of file

   17. tail :
   --> this command is used to display last few lines (10 lines) of the file.
   syntax: tail <file_name>
   eg: tail myfile.txt

   18. sort : 
   -->used to sort file
   syntax: sort <file_name>
   eg: sort names.txt

   19. uniq :
   --> used to delete all adjacent duplicate lines in a file
   syntax: uniq <file_name>
   eg: uniq file.txt

   20. clear / ctrl + l :
   ---> used to clear screen.
   syntax: clear
       OR
   use ctrl + l



  
